	<!-- //About -->
    <!-- CODES -->
	<div class="about" id="codes">
		<div class="container">

			<h1>Codes</h1>
			<p>CTA scientists use a variety of codes to model radiation transport.  Some are in open repositories and we hope to make more available.
			<div class="underline1"></div>

            <div class="projlist">
            <ul>
	      <li class="projtitle"> <h4>Semi-Analytic  <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2017ApJ...850..133D"> code reference  </a>
 </h4> Semi-Analytic is 1-temperature diffusion code running on top of homologous outflows.  This code is very quick and can run large grids of models to get first pass light-curves.
</li>
	      <li class="projtitle"> <h4>Spectrum + RAGE/Cassio  <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2013ApJS..204...16F"> code reference  </a>
 </h4> Spectrum is a post-process spectra code using LANL opacities and building upon the radiation-hydrodynamics codes (<a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2008CS%26D....1a5005G"> RAGE/Cassio </a>) at LANL.  This code is ideal for problems where shock heating is important.
</li>
	      <li class="projtitle"> <h4>SuperNu                   <a href="https://bitbucket.org/drrossum/supernu/wiki/Home"> code link  </a>
 </h4> SuperNu is a program for
                simulating time-dependent radiation transport in local
                thermodynamic equilibrium with matter.  It applies the
                methods of Implicit Monte Carlo (IMC) and Discrete
                Diffusion Monte Carlo (DDMC) for static or
                homologously expanding spatial grids.  The radiation
                field affects material temperature but does not affect
                the motion of the fluid.  SuperNu may be applied to
                simulate radiation transport for supernovae with
                ejecta velocities that are not affected by radiation
                momentum.  The physical opacity calculation includes
                elements from Hydrogen up to Cobalt.  SuperNu is
                motivated by the ongoing research into the effect of
                variation in the structure of progenitor star
                explosions on observables: the brightness and shape of
                light curves and the temporal evolution of the
                spectra.  Consequently, the code may be used to
                post-process data from hydrodynamic simulations.
                SuperNu does not include any capabilities or methods
                that allow for non-trivial hydrodynamics.
</li>

<br>
            </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DATA -->
	<div class="about" id="data">
		<div class="container">

			<h1>DATA</h1>
			<p>CTA scientists are engaged in a wide variety of projects, producing different data sets.  The links below download tar files of this data:</p>
			<div class="underline1"></div>

            <div class="projlist">
            <ul>
                <li class="projtitle"> <a href="macronova_models_wollaeger2017.tgz"> Kilonova models  </a> from <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018MNRAS.478.3298W"> Wollaeger et al. (2018) </a> LAUR-17-27847 </li>
<br>
                <li class="projtitle"> <a href="remnant_source.tar.gz">
 Source term study </a> Kilonova models including additional source terms from either a pulsar or fallback accretion from <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2019arXiv190405934W"> Wollaeger et al. (2019) </a> LAUR-19-22878 </li>
<br>
                <li class="projtitle"> <a href="composition_sensitivity.tar.gz">
 Source term study </a> Kilonova models varying individual lanthanide abundances from <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1904.13298"> Even et al. (2019) </a> LAUR-19-22878 </li>
<br>
            </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>



